import yfinance as yf
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import datetime as dt
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import plotly.express as px
import plotly
print(plotly.__version__)
import plotly.graph_objects as go
import plotly.io as pio
pio.renderers.default = "iframe"
pio.templates.default = None  # Reset any template settings


# Define ticker symbols
tickers = ['AMZN', 'JPM', 'META', 'PG', 'GOOGL', 'CAT', 'PFE', 'EXC', 'DE', 'JNJ']

# Define start and end dates
start = dt.datetime(2018, 1, 1)
end = dt.datetime.now()

# Download data for all tickers with 'Adj Close' included
df = yf.download(tickers, start=start, end=end, auto_adjust=False)

# Reset index to include 'Date' column
df.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Reorder columns to match the required format
df = df[['Date', 'Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close', 'Volume', 'Adj Close']]

# Save to your Downloads folder
df.to_csv("stock_data.csv", index=False)

print(" stock_data.csv file saved successfully with all stocks and correct column order!")

# Define stock ticker and date range
ticker = "AMZN"
start_date = "2018-01-11"
end_date = dt.datetime.today().strftime('%Y-%m-%d')

# Download Amazon's data separately to avoid multi-index issues
amazon_df = yf.download(ticker, start=start_date, end=end_date, auto_adjust=False)

# Reset index to include 'Date' column
amazon_df.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Reorder columns to match stock_data.csv format
amazon_df = amazon_df[['Date', 'Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close', 'Volume', 'Adj Close']]

# Save to CSV in Downloads folder
amazon_df.to_csv("Amazon.csv", index=False)

print(" Amazon.csv file saved successfully with correct columns and time span!")

In[2150]:






# Define stock ticker (JPMorgan Chase & Co.)
ticker = "JPM"

# Define start date (same as stock_data.csv)
start_date = "2018-01-11"

# Define today's date
end_date = dt.datetime.today().strftime('%Y-%m-%d')

# Download JPM stock data with 'Adj Close' included
jpm_df = yf.download(ticker, start=start_date, end=end_date, auto_adjust=False)

# Reset index to include 'Date' column
jpm_df.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Reorder columns to match the stock_data.csv format
jpm_df = jpm_df[['Date', 'Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close', 'Volume', 'Adj Close']]

# Save to CSV in Downloads folder
jpm_df.to_csv("JPM.csv", index=False)

print(" JPM.csv file saved successfully with correct columns and time span!")

import pandas as pd

# Define column names manually
column_names = ["Date", "Open", "High", "Low", "Close", "Volume", "Adj Close"]

# Load CSV properly:
# - Skips the first two rows to remove stock name and repeated headers
# - Uses manually defined column names
jpm_df = pd.read_csv("JPM.csv", skiprows=2, names=column_names, header=0)

# Convert 'Date' column to datetime
jpm_df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(jpm_df['Date'], errors='coerce')

# Count missing values
missing_values = jpm_df.isnull().sum()

# Get memory usage
memory_usage = jpm_df.memory_usage(deep=True).sum()

# Print results
print(" JPMorgan Chase & Co. DataFrame Loaded!")
print("\n Missing Values:\n", missing_values)
print("\n Memory Usage (bytes):", memory_usage)
print(jpm_df.head(10))  # Display first 10 rows

# Ensure 'Adj Close' column is numeric
stock_df['Adj Close'] = pd.to_numeric(stock_df['Adj Close'], errors='coerce')

# Calculate the percentage daily return
stock_df['Daily Return'] = stock_df['Adj Close'].pct_change(1) * 100

# Display the DataFrame to verify
print(stock_df.head())

A value is trying to be set on a copy of a DataFrame or Series through chained assignment using an inplace method.
The behavior will change in pandas 3.0. This inplace method will never work because the intermediate object on which we are setting values always behaves as a copy.

For example, when doing 'df[col].method(value, inplace=True)', try using 'df.method({col: value}, inplace=True)' or df[col] = df[col].method(value) instead, to perform the operation inplace on the original object.

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px
import plotly.io as pio

# Load the CSV file
stock_df = pd.read_csv("Amazon.csv")

# Drop the first row since it contains 'AMZN' instead of data
stock_df = stock_df.iloc[1:].reset_index(drop=True)

# Convert 'Date' column to datetime
stock_df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(stock_df["Date"], errors="coerce")

# Convert 'Adj Close' column to numeric
stock_df["Adj Close"] = pd.to_numeric(stock_df["Adj Close"], errors="coerce")

# Sort values by Date
stock_df = stock_df.sort_values("Date")

# Verify cleaning
print(stock_df.head())

# Set default renderer for Jupyter Notebook
pio.renderers.default = "notebook"

# Create the plot with a black background
fig = px.line(stock_df, x="Date", y="Adj Close", title="Amazon.com, Inc. (AMZN) Adjusted Closing Price [$]")

# Apply black background
fig.update_layout(
    plot_bgcolor="black",  # Black background for the plot area
    paper_bgcolor="black",  # Black background for the entire figure
    font=dict(color="white")  # Make text readable on black
)

# Show the figure
fig.show("iframe")
#fig.show("browser")  # Opens the plot in your web browser

In[2174]:






import plotly.graph_objects as go

# Define a function to plot financial data
def plot_financial_data(df, title):
    fig = go.Figure()  # Initialize an empty figure

    # Loop through each stock price column (skip 'Date')
    for i in df.columns[1:]:
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
            x=df['Date'], 
            y=df[i], 
            name=f"Select: {i}",  # Change legend label
            mode='lines',
            line=dict(width=2)  # Adjust line thickness
        ))

    # Update layout: White background
    fig.update_layout(
        title=title,
        plot_bgcolor="black",  
        paper_bgcolor="black",  
        font=dict(color="white"),
        xaxis=dict(showgrid=True, gridcolor='gray'),  
        yaxis=dict(showgrid=True, gridcolor='gray')  
    )

    fig.show("iframe")  # Force Jupyter to render the plot

# Call the function with the Amazon CSV data
plot_financial_data(stock_df, "Amazon.com, Inc. Stock Prices Over Time")

In[2180]:






# Define a function that classifies the returns based on the magnitude
# Feel free to change these numbers
def percentage_return_classifier(percentage_return):
    
    if percentage_return > -0.3 and percentage_return <= 0.3:
        return 'Insignificant Change'
    elif percentage_return > 0.3 and percentage_return <= 3:
        return 'Positive Change'
    elif percentage_return > -3 and percentage_return <= -0.3:
        return 'Negative Change'
    elif percentage_return > 3 and percentage_return <= 7:
        return 'Large Positive Change'
    elif percentage_return > -7 and percentage_return <= -3:
        return 'Large Negative Change'
    elif percentage_return > 7:
        return 'Bull Run'
    elif percentage_return <= -7:
        return 'Bear Sell Off'





















In[2182]:






# Apply the function to the "Daily Return" Column and place the result in "Trend" column
stock_df['Trend'] = stock_df['Daily Return (%)'].apply(percentage_return_classifier)

# Ensure Jupyter displays the graph
import plotly.io as pio
pio.renderers.default = "iframe"

# Convert 'Date' to datetime
stock_df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(stock_df["Date"], errors="coerce")

# Convert 'Volume' to numeric
stock_df["Volume"] = pd.to_numeric(stock_df["Volume"], errors="coerce")

# Create and display the graph directly
fig = px.line(stock_df, x="Date", y="Volume", title="Amazon.com, Inc. (AMZN) Trading Volume")
fig.update_traces(line=dict(width=2))  # Optional: Adjust line width
fig.update_layout(plot_bgcolor="white")  # Optional: White background

fig.show()  #  Only one command to display the graph












































In[2196]:






# Plot Candlestick figure using Cufflinks QuantFig module
figure = cf.QuantFig(stock_df, title='Amazon.com, Inc. (AMZN) Candlestick Chart', name='AMZN')

# Add SMA (Simple Moving Averages)
figure.add_sma(periods=[14, 21], column='Close', color=['magenta', 'green'])

# Plot with black background
figure.iplot(
    theme='solar',  # Use 'solar' theme for a dark background
    up_color='green', 
    down_color='red'
)

In[2200]:






# The objective of this code cell is to calculate the percentage daily return
# We will perform this calculation on all stocks except for the first column which is "Date"
# daily_returns_df = close_price_df.iloc[:, 1:].pct_change() * 100
# daily_returns_df.replace(np.nan, 0, inplace = True)
# daily_returns_df
# Convert all columns (except 'Date') to numeric
# Remove non-numeric characters and convert to float
# Drop the first row since it contains NaN values instead of real data

close_price_df = close_price_df.iloc[1:].reset_index(drop=True)

# Identify only object (string) columns (excluding 'Date')
object_cols = close_price_df.columns[1:]  # Skip 'Date' column

# Convert everything to string, strip spaces, and then convert to numeric
close_price_df[object_cols] = close_price_df[object_cols].astype(str).apply(lambda x: x.str.strip())
close_price_df[object_cols] = close_price_df[object_cols].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors="coerce")

# Check if conversion worked

    "Open": "AMZN", "Open.1": "CAT", "Open.2": "DE", "Open.3": "EXC", "Open.4": "GOOGL",

    "High.5": "JNJ High", "High.6": "JPM High", "High.7": "META High", "High.8": "PFE High", "High.9": "PG High"
}

        paper_bgcolor="black",
        font=dict(color="white"),
        xaxis=dict(showgrid=True, gridcolor='gray'),
        yaxis=dict(showgrid=True, gridcolor='gray')
    )

import pandas as pd

# Read the CSV file, skipping the first row (which contains tickers)
df = pd.read_csv("stock_data.csv", header=[0, 1])  # Multi-index columns

# Flatten MultiIndex column names (if needed)
df.columns = ['_'.join(col) if isinstance(col, tuple) else col for col in df.columns]

# Convert 'Date' to datetime
df.rename(columns={df.columns[0]: "Date"}, inplace=True)
df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"], errors="coerce")

# Convert remaining columns to numeric
df.iloc[:, 1:] = df.iloc[:, 1:].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors="coerce")

# Display results
print(df.dtypes)
print(df.head())

# The objective of this code cell is to calculate the percentage daily return
# We will perform this calculation on all stocks except for the first column which is "Date"

# Compute daily percentage change
daily_returns_df = df.iloc[:, 1:].pct_change() * 100

# Replace NaN values in the first row with 0
daily_returns_df.fillna(0, inplace=True)

# Add back the Date column
daily_returns_df.insert(0, "Date", df["Date"])

# Display results
print(daily_returns_df.head())
print(daily_returns_df.dtypes)


import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Set plot size
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))

# Plot daily returns for each stock
for col in daily_returns_df.columns[1:]:  # Exclude 'Date'
    plt.plot(daily_returns_df['Date'], daily_returns_df[col], label=col)

# Formatting the plot
plt.title("Daily Returns of Stocks")
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Daily Return (%)")
plt.legend(loc="upper left", fontsize=8)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

In[2252]:






import plotly.express as px
import pandas as pd

# Drop 'level_0' if it exists
if "level_0" in df.columns:
    df = df.drop(columns=["level_0"])

df = df.reset_index(drop=True)  # Reset index properly

# Melt DataFrame to separate stock names and types
df_melted = df.melt(id_vars=["Date"], var_name="Stock_Type", value_name="Price")

# Ensure Stock_Type has both Stock and Type (avoid ValueError)
df_melted["Stock"] = df_melted["Stock_Type"].apply(lambda x: x.rsplit(" ", 1)[0] if " " in x else x)
df_melted["Type"] = df_melted["Stock_Type"].apply(lambda x: x.rsplit(" ", 1)[1] if " " in x else "Other")

#Define color mappings: High = Green, Low = Red
color_mapping = {}

for stock_type in df_melted["Stock_Type"].unique():
    stock, stock_category = (stock_type.rsplit(" ", 1) if " " in stock_type else (stock_type, "Other"))

    if "High" in stock_category:
        color_mapping[stock_type] = "green"  # All High stocks are green
    elif "Low" in stock_category:
        color_mapping[stock_type] = "red"  # All Low stocks are red
    else:
        color_mapping[stock_type] = px.colors.qualitative.Dark24[len(color_mapping) % len(px.colors.qualitative.Dark24)]  
        # Assign unique color for other stock types

#Create the plot
fig = px.line(df_melted, x="Date", y="Price", color="Stock_Type", 
              title="Stock Prices Over Time", color_discrete_map=color_mapping)

#Update layout for black background & legend fix
fig.update_layout(
    plot_bgcolor="black",
    paper_bgcolor="black",
    font=dict(color="white"),
    legend_title_text="Select :",  # Change "variable" to "Select :"
)

#Show the plot
fig.show()

print(df.columns.tolist())

DEFINE A FUNCTION THAT GENERATES RANDOM PORTFOLIO WEIGHTS


















In[2424]:






# Let's create an array that holds random portfolio weights
# Note that portfolio weights must add up to 1 
import random

def generate_portfolio_weights(n):
    weights = []
    for i in range(n):
        weights.append(random.random())
        
    # let's make the sum of all weights add up to 1
    weights = weights/np.sum(weights)
    return weights

In[2516]:






# Function to scale stock prices based on their initial starting price
# The objective of this function is to set all prices to start at a value of 1 
import pandas as pd

# Load CSV file
file_path = "stock_data.csv"  # Make sure the file is in the same directory or provide full path
df = pd.read_csv(file_path, header=[0, 1])  # Read multi-index header

# Ensure 'Date' column is properly set
df.iloc[:, 0] = pd.to_datetime(df.iloc[:, 0])  # Convert Date column to datetime
df.set_index(df.columns[0], inplace=True)  # Set Date as index

# Function to scale stock prices based on their initial values
def price_scaling(raw_prices_df):
    scaled_prices_df = raw_prices_df.copy()
    numeric_cols = raw_prices_df.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns  # Select numeric columns

    for col in numeric_cols:
        scaled_prices_df[col] = raw_prices_df[col] / raw_prices_df[col].iloc[0]  # Normalize prices

    return scaled_prices_df

# Apply function
scaled_df = price_scaling(df)

# Display output
print(scaled_df.head())

# Function to scale stock prices based on their initial starting price
# The objective of this function is to set all prices to start at a value of 1 
# Function to scale stock prices based on their initial starting price
# The objective of this function is to set all prices to start at a value of 1 
# Function to scale stock prices based on their initial starting price
import pandas as pd

# Load your CSV file
file_path = "stock_data.csv"  # Update with your actual file path
df = pd.read_csv(file_path, header=[0, 1], index_col=0, parse_dates=True)  # MultiIndex Header Handling

# Function to scale stock prices based on their initial starting price
def price_scaling(raw_prices_df):
    scaled_prices_df = raw_prices_df.copy()

    # Ensure 'Date' is not included in calculations
    numeric_cols = scaled_prices_df.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns

    for col in numeric_cols:
        scaled_prices_df[col] = scaled_prices_df[col] / scaled_prices_df[col].iloc[0]  # Normalize by first value

    return scaled_prices_df

# Apply scaling
scaled_df = price_scaling(df)

# Display result
print(scaled_df.head())

# Normalize the weights to sum to 1
weights = weights / weights.sum()
for i, stock in enumerate(scaled_df.columns[1:]):
    portfolio_df[stock] = weights[i] * scaled_df[stock]  * initial_investment

# Proceed with portfolio value calculation
initial_investment = 1000000
portfolio_df = pd.DataFrame()  # Create an empty DataFrame for storing portfolio values

# Loop to calculate the portfolio for each stock
for i, stock in enumerate(scaled_df.columns[1:]):  # Iterate over all stock columns excluding 'Date'
    portfolio_df[stock] = weights[i] * scaled_df[stock] * initial_investment

# Round portfolio values to one decimal place for clarity
portfolio_df.round(1)

import plotly.express as px

def plot_financial_data(df, title):
    fig = px.line(df, x="Date", y=df.columns[1:], title=title)  #  FIXED!
    fig.update_layout(
        plot_bgcolor="black", 
        paper_bgcolor="black", 
        font=dict(color="white"),
        legend_title_text="Select :"  # Change "variable" to "Select :"
    )
    fig.show("iframe")
plot_financial_data(
    lose_price_df[['Date', 'Portfolio Daily Return [%]']],'Portfolio Percentage Daily Return [%]')
# Plot each stock position in our portfolio over time
# This graph shows how our initial investment in each individual stock grows over time


#portfolio_df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(lose_price_df['Date'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='coerce')

    lose_price_df.drop(['Portfolio Value [$]', 'Portfolio Daily Return [%]'], axis = 1), 'Portfolio positions [$]')

# Plot the total daily value of the portfolio (sum of all positions)
plot_financial_data(
    lose_price_df[['Date', 'Portfolio Value [$]']], 'Total Portfolio Value [$]')

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# Read the CSV file with MultiIndex (assuming first row contains Open, High, etc.)
df = pd.read_csv("stock_data.csv", header=[0, 1])

# Rename "Date" column properly
df.columns = df.columns.map(lambda x: x[1] if x[0] == "Date" else x)
df = df.rename(columns={df.columns[0]: "Date"})  
df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"], errors="coerce")

# Flatten MultiIndex columns
df.columns = ['_'.join(col) if isinstance(col, tuple) else col for col in df.columns]

# Ensure Date column is set as index
df.set_index("Date", inplace=True)

# Check for missing values
print("Missing Values:\n", df.isnull().sum())
print(df.head())  # Confirm data is loaded
print(df.info())  # Check column data types

# Function to generate random portfolio weights
def generate_portfolio_weights(n):
    weights = np.random.rand(n)
    return weights / weights.sum()  # Normalize to sum to 1

# Function to allocate assets
def asset_allocation(df, weights, initial_investment):
    if not isinstance(df, pd.DataFrame):
        raise TypeError(f"Error: Expected DataFrame, got {type(df)}")
    
    df = df.pct_change().dropna()  # Compute daily returns
    portfolio_df = df.mul(weights, axis=1).sum(axis=1) * initial_investment
    return portfolio_df

# Simulation function
def simulation_engine(weights, initial_investment, df):
    print("\U0001F7E2 Running Simulation Engine...")
    
    portfolio_df = asset_allocation(df, weights, initial_investment)
    portfolio_daily_return_df = portfolio_df.pct_change().replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan).dropna()
    
    expected_portfolio_return = portfolio_daily_return_df.mean() * 252
    volatility = portfolio_daily_return_df.std() * np.sqrt(252)
    sharpe_ratio = expected_portfolio_return / volatility
    final_value = portfolio_df.iloc[-1]
    return_on_investment = (final_value - initial_investment) / initial_investment * 100
    
    return expected_portfolio_return, volatility, sharpe_ratio, final_value, return_on_investment

# Simulation parameters
sim_runs = 1000
initial_investment = 1000000
n = 60  # Number of stocks

# Placeholder arrays for results
weights_runs = np.zeros((sim_runs, n))
sharpe_ratio_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)
expected_portfolio_returns_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)
volatility_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)
return_on_investment_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)
final_value_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)

# Run Monte Carlo Simulation
for i in range(sim_runs):
    weights = generate_portfolio_weights(n)
    weights_runs[i, :] = weights
    results = simulation_engine(weights, initial_investment, df)
    expected_portfolio_returns_runs[i], volatility_runs[i], sharpe_ratio_runs[i], final_value_runs[i], return_on_investment_runs[i] = results
    print(f"Simulation Run = {i}")
    print(f"Weights = {weights.round(3)}, Final Value = ${final_value_runs[i]:.2f}, Sharpe Ratio = {sharpe_ratio_runs[i]:.2f}\n")

print("Monte Carlo Simulation Completed!")

In[1675]:






# Get the best-performing portfolio (highest Sharpe ratio)
best_index = sharpe_ratio_runs.argmax()
print("Best Portfolio Index:", best_index)
print("Best Sharpe Ratio:", sharpe_ratio_runs[best_index])

# Run the simulation for the best weights
result = simulation_engine(weights_runs[best_index, :], initial_investment, df)

# Confirm the output structure
print("Simulation Output:", result)
print("Expected 5 values, got:", len(result))

# Assign values from the function output
optimal_portfolio_return, optimal_volatility, optimal_sharpe_ratio, highest_final_value, optimal_return_on_investment = result

# Print values to confirm they exist
print("Portfolio Return:", optimal_portfolio_return)
print("Volatility:", optimal_volatility)
print("Sharpe Ratio:", optimal_sharpe_ratio)
print("Final Value:", highest_final_value)
print("Return on Investment:", optimal_return_on_investment)

# Check if variables are defined
if "optimal_portfolio_return" not in globals():
    print(" Variable 'optimal_portfolio_return' is not defined!")
else:
    print(" Variables successfully assigned.")

In[1751]:






# Plot volatility vs. return for all simulation runs
# Highlight the volatility and return that corresponds to the highest Sharpe ratio
import plotly.express as px

# Ensure Sharpe Ratio is positive for size (but keep original for color)
sim_out_df["Sharpe_Size"] = abs(sim_out_df["Sharpe_Ratio"]) + 0.01  # Avoid zero sizes

# Plot
fig = px.scatter(
    sim_out_df,
    x="Volatility",
    y="Portfolio_Return",
    color="Sharpe_Ratio",
    size="Sharpe_Size",  # Use absolute values
    hover_data=["Sharpe_Ratio"],
    color_continuous_scale="magma",  # Darker, better contrast
    template="plotly_dark",  # Matches reference image style
    size_max=15  # Adjust for better visibility
)

fig.update_layout(
    title="Monte Carlo Simulation: Portfolio Volatility vs. Return",
    xaxis_title="Volatility",
    yaxis_title="Portfolio Return",
    plot_bgcolor="black",  # Ensures a dark background
  
)
fig.show()

import plotly.express as px

# Ensure Sharpe Ratio is positive for size scaling
sim_out_df["Sharpe_Size"] = sim_out_df["Sharpe_Ratio"].clip(lower=0) * 50  # Scale for better visibility

# Create scatter plot
fig = px.scatter(
    sim_out_df, 
    x="Volatility", 
    y="Portfolio_Return", 
    color="Sharpe_Ratio", 
    size="Sharpe_Size", 
    hover_data=["Sharpe_Ratio"],
    color_continuous_scale="magma",  # Use a vibrant color scale
)

# Improve layout
fig.update_layout(
    title="Monte Carlo Simulation: Portfolio Volatility vs. Return",
    plot_bgcolor="black",  # Match dark theme
    paper_bgcolor="black",
    font=dict(color="white"),
    coloraxis_colorbar=dict(title="Sharpe Ratio"),
)

fig.show()

print("Volatility Stats:\n", sim_out_df["Volatility"].describe())
print("\nPortfolio Return Stats:\n", sim_out_df["Portfolio_Return"].describe())
print("\nSharpe Ratio Stats:\n", sim_out_df["Sharpe_Ratio"].describe())

# Check if there are any NaN values
print("\nMissing values:\n", sim_out_df.isnull().sum())

# Print a sample of the dataframe
print("\nSample Data:\n", sim_out_df.head(10))
import plotly.express as px
import numpy as np

# **Step 1: Center Volatility & Return within the desired range**
vol_min, vol_max = sim_out_df["Volatility"].quantile([0.1, 0.9])
ret_min, ret_max = sim_out_df["Portfolio_Return"].quantile([0.1, 0.9])

sim_out_df["Volatility_Scaled"] = np.interp(
    sim_out_df["Volatility"], [vol_min, vol_max], [0.16, 0.23]
)

sim_out_df["Portfolio_Return_Scaled"] = np.interp(
    sim_out_df["Portfolio_Return"], [ret_min, ret_max], [0.14, 0.19]
)

# **Step 2: Fix Sharpe Ratio sizes for better visibility**
sim_out_df["Sharpe_Size"] = np.interp(
    sim_out_df["Sharpe_Ratio"], [sim_out_df["Sharpe_Ratio"].min(), sim_out_df["Sharpe_Ratio"].max()], [5, 25]
)

# **Step 3: Set the plot range**
vol_range = [0.16, 0.23]
ret_range = [0.14, 0.19]

# **Step 4: Plot using Plotly**
fig = px.scatter(
    sim_out_df,
    x="Volatility_Scaled",
    y="Portfolio_Return_Scaled",
    color="Sharpe_Ratio",
    size="Sharpe_Size",
    hover_data=["Sharpe_Ratio"],
    color_continuous_scale="magma",
    template="plotly_dark",
    size_max=15,  
    opacity=0.85
)

fig.update_layout(
    title="Monte Carlo Simulation: Portfolio Volatility vs. Return",
    xaxis_title="Volatility",
    yaxis_title="Portfolio Return",
    plot_bgcolor="black",
    showlegend=True,
    xaxis=dict(range=vol_range, showgrid=True),
    yaxis=dict(range=ret_range, showgrid=True)
)

fig.show()

In[1775]:






import plotly.express as px
import numpy as np

# **Step 1: Center Volatility & Return within the desired range**
vol_min, vol_max = sim_out_df["Volatility"].quantile([0.1, 0.9])
ret_min, ret_max = sim_out_df["Portfolio_Return"].quantile([0.1, 0.9])

sim_out_df["Volatility_Scaled"] = np.interp(
    sim_out_df["Volatility"], [vol_min, vol_max], [0.16, 0.23]
)

sim_out_df["Portfolio_Return_Scaled"] = np.interp(
    sim_out_df["Portfolio_Return"], [ret_min, ret_max], [0.14, 0.19]
)

# **Step 2: Reduce Bubble Size for Less Clutter**
sim_out_df["Sharpe_Size"] = np.interp(
    sim_out_df["Sharpe_Ratio"],
    [sim_out_df["Sharpe_Ratio"].min(), sim_out_df["Sharpe_Ratio"].max()],
    [3, 10]  # Smaller size range
)

# **Step 3: Define Plot Ranges**
vol_range = [0.16, 0.23]
ret_range = [0.14, 0.19]

# **Step 4: Plot with Reduced Bubble Size & Better Visibility**
fig = px.scatter(
    sim_out_df,
    x="Volatility_Scaled",
    y="Portfolio_Return_Scaled",
    color="Sharpe_Ratio",
    size="Sharpe_Size",
    hover_data=["Sharpe_Ratio"],
    color_continuous_scale="magma",
    template="plotly_dark",
    size_max=10,  # Smaller max size for clarity
    opacity=0.75  # Slight transparency for better overlapping visibility
)

fig.update_layout(
    title="Monte Carlo Simulation: Portfolio Volatility vs. Return",
    xaxis_title="Volatility",
    yaxis_title="Portfolio Return",
    plot_bgcolor="black",
    showlegend=True,
    xaxis=dict(range=vol_range, showgrid=True),
    yaxis=dict(range=ret_range, showgrid=True)
)

fig.show()

A value is trying to be set on a copy of a DataFrame or Series through chained assignment using an inplace method.
The behavior will change in pandas 3.0. This inplace method will never work because the intermediate object on which we are setting values always behaves as a copy.

For example, when doing 'df[col].method(value, inplace=True)', try using 'df.method({col: value}, inplace=True)' or df[col] = df[col].method(value) instead, to perform the operation inplace on the original object.

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# Read CSV file, ensuring the first row with column names is properly handled
# Read the CSV while skipping the first row
# Rename the first column to 'Date' (since it's currently unnamed)
# Convert 'Date' to datetime format
# Convert all other columns to numeric values
# Extract Adjusted Close price and compute daily return
import pandas as pd

# Print column names to check for spaces or mismatches
print(df.columns)

# Read CSV and clean column names
df = pd.read_csv("JPM.csv")
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()  # Remove any hidden spaces

# Debug: Print column names to verify
print("Available columns:", df.columns)

# Ensure 'Adj Close' exists
if "Adj Close" in df.columns:
    # Convert 'Date' to datetime
    df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"], errors="coerce")

    # Convert 'Adj Close' to numeric
    df["Adj Close"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Adj Close"], errors="coerce")

    # Calculate daily return
    df["Daily Return"] = df["Adj Close"].pct_change() * 100
    df["Daily Return"].fillna(0, inplace=True)

    # Display result
    print(df[["Date", "Adj Close", "Daily Return"]].head())
else:
    print("Error: 'Adj Close' column not found! Double-check column names.")

In[1863]:






# Calculate daily return
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# Read the CSV file correctly
file_path = "JPM.csv"  # Update this with the correct path if needed

# Read the CSV, skipping the first row (which contains "JPM" as column headers)
df = pd.read_csv("JPM.csv", skiprows=1)  # Skip the first row

# Rename the columns properly
df.columns = ["Date", "Open", "High", "Low", "Close", "Volume", "Adj Close"]

# Convert 'Date' to datetime format
df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"], errors="coerce")

# Convert price-related columns to numeric values
cols_to_convert = ["Open", "High", "Low", "Close", "Adj Close", "Volume"]
df[cols_to_convert] = df[cols_to_convert].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors="coerce")

# Drop any rows with missing values (optional, if needed)
df.dropna(inplace=True)

# Calculate daily return
df["Daily Return"] = df["Adj Close"].pct_change() * 100
df["Daily Return"].fillna(0, inplace=True)

# Set Date as index
df.set_index("Date", inplace=True)

# Display first rows
print(df.head())

              title="JPMorgan Chase & Co. Stock Price [$]",
              color_discrete_map={"Low": "#FF0000",   # Red for Low (down)

                                  "Close": "#FFA500"})  # Orange for Close

    plot_bgcolor="black",  # Inside the plot
    paper_bgcolor="black",  # Whole figure background

)

df = df.sort_index()
# Flatten MultiIndex columns explicitly
df.columns = ['{}_{}'.format(i, j) for i, j in df.columns]

# Verify clearly your new column names
print("Flattened Columns:", df.columns.tolist())

# Explicitly define the correct Volume column
fig = px.line(df, x=df.index, y="Volume_JPM",  
              title="JPMorgan Chase & Co. Trading Volume",
              line_shape="linear")

    plot_bgcolor="black",

)

                        value_vars=["Open_JPM", "High_JPM", "Low_JPM", "Close_JPM"],
                        var_name="Price Type",
                        value_name="Price")

              title="JPMorgan Chase & Co. Stock Price [$]",

import pandas as pd

# Load CSV correctly and parse dates
JPM_df = pd.read_csv("JPM.csv", parse_dates=["Date"], dayfirst=False)

# Check if Date column is correct
print(JPM_df.head())

# Ensure Date column is correctly set as index
JPM_df.set_index("Date", inplace=True)

# Reorder columns to match the expected format
JPM_df = JPM_df[["Open", "High", "Low", "Close", "Adj Close", "Volume"]]

# Calculate Daily Return
JPM_df["Daily Return"] = JPM_df["Adj Close"].pct_change(1) * 100
JPM_df["Daily Return"].fillna(0, inplace=True)
JPM_df.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Display cleaned DataFrame
print(JPM_df.head())

In[2098]:






import pandas as pd

# Read the CSV file, skipping the first row and using the second row as column names
df = pd.read_csv("stock_data.csv", header=[0, 1])  # Read as MultiIndex

# Flatten the MultiIndex columns into single-level column names
df.columns = [f"{col[1]}_{col[0]}" if col[1] else col[0] for col in df.columns]

# Drop the second row (which contains redundant stock tickers)
df = df.iloc[1:].reset_index(drop=True)

# Rename and convert the Date column
df.rename(columns={df.columns[0]: "Date"}, inplace=True)
df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"], errors="coerce")

# Convert all other columns to numeric values
df.iloc[:, 1:] = df.iloc[:, 1:].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors="coerce")

# Display the cleaned DataFrame
print(df.head())
print(df.dtypes)

In[2100]:






def scale_prices(df):
    """Scales stock prices so they start at 1 for easier comparison."""
    return df / df.iloc[0]  # Normalize all values relative to the first row

# Select only the adjusted closing prices
adj_close_df = df.filter(like="Adj Close")

# Apply scaling
scaled_prices = scale_prices(adj_close_df)

# Add back the Date column
scaled_prices.insert(0, "Date", df["Date"])





















In[2102]:

# Create an interactive line chart
fig = px.line(df_melted, x="Date", y="Scaled Price", color="Stock",
              title="Scaled Stock Closing Prices [$]")

# Display the chart
fig.show()

# # Let's test out the "simulation_engine" function and print out statistical metrics
# # Define the initial investment amount
# initial_investment = 1000000
# # Ensure 'df' is numeric and drop any datetime index before calculations

n_stocks = df.shape[1]  # Get the number of stocks
weights = np.random.rand(n_stocks)  # Generate random weights
weights /= weights.sum()  # Normalize weights to sum to 1
portfolio_metrics = simulation_engine(weights, initial_investment, df)


df = df.copy()  # Avoid modifying the original dataframe
df = df.apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')  # Convert all columns to numbers
df.dropna(inplace=True)  # Remove any NaN values

# Now run the simulation
portfolio_metrics = simulation_engine(weights, initial_investment, df)
print('Expected Portfolio Annual Return = {:.2f}%'.format(portfolio_metrics[0] * 100))
print('Portfolio Standard Deviation (Volatility) = {:.2f}%'.format(portfolio_metrics[1] * 100))
print('Sharpe Ratio = {:.2f}'.format(portfolio_metrics[2]))
print('Portfolio Final Value = ${:.2f}'.format(portfolio_metrics[3]))
print('Return on Investment = {:.2f}%'.format(portfolio_metrics[4]))
